{
  "texts": [
    "In the case of Barre and Hosh, the RPD used the photo comparison to prove the unreliability of the asylum seekers' claim, which was a crucial element for revoking their status.",
    "In this case, the facial recognition software generated evidence.",
    "With the term automated evidence, I refer to cases where the output of an automated system is used to prove a fact that is relevant to the final decision.",
    "126 The concept of evidence encompasses both judicial and administrative proceedings in line with the terminology used by CJEU in their 122 Federal Court of Canada, Asha Ali Barre and Alia Musa Hosh v. The Minister of Citizenship and Immigration, Case No. 2022 FC 1078, para.",
    "20, 2022), https://decisions.fct-cf.gc.ca/fc-cf/decisions/en/item/521971/index.do (last accessed Feb. 27, 2024) [when Asha and Alia applied for judicial review, the court found the decision to vacate their status unreasonable and in breach of procedural fairness]."
  ]
}